ck to school.</div><div><br></div><div>I\'ve worked hard to the point of being at the register a bit more frequently. Or am I working hard to the point of earning a vacation?</div><div><br></div><div>No matter. As the old saying goes. Productivity is key at work, not dignity.</div>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:71:\"http://miletich2.blogspot.com/2014/08/outlook-at-work-seems-somber.html\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:6:\"author\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:26:\"noreply@blogger.com (Zack)\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:1:{s:7:\"updated\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"2014-08-17T20:20:52.531-07:00\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0\";a:1:{s:5:\"total\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:17;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:70:\"tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-3424051896540341526.post-6647603688708089623\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Tue, 12 Aug 2014 04:16:00 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Two paths\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1122:\"One path is to continue working at Nifty Thrift for a great amount of moolah helping customers and some exercise. The other is to find a career in computer technical support. To do it, I would need to refine my skills in the computer industry, which requires that you go back to school. Which is more suitable?<div><br></div><div>So far, I\'m glad to have found work at Nifty Thrift, from shelfing merchandise to checking out customers. Some are regulars and some we only see every once and a while. Out of county or out of state. But for an opportunity to work in an IT department, I\'ll need to go through the tedious obstacle known as education to get myself there. For example, to be a network administrator, it\'s gonna require mathematical skills, if not some.</div><div><br></div><div>A lesson learned in life is that no matter how old you are, no matter what you\'ve done, <b>there is always a chance you\'ll be beckoned to go back to school/college</b> to further your chances at employment. I\'m not ready for such a thing now. Nor will I ever find the motivation to go back. Especially for a job with computers.</div>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:52:\"http://miletich2.blogspot.com/2014/08/two-paths.html\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:6:\"author\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:26:\"noreply@blogger.com (Zack)\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:1:{s:7:\"updated\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"2014-08-11T21:16:36.586-07:00\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0\";a:1:{s:5:\"total\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:18;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:70:\"tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-3424051896540341526.post-8750379373319922743\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Mon, 04 Aug 2014 05:01:00 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:21:\"Stupid climate change\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1335:\"To me, it\'s a nuisance. Nothing more. Because were in a drought, I have a feeling California\'s gonna turn into a desert, as well as the rest of the west coast. I blame climate change for that. All the latter does is serve the detriment of mankind and is the same as global warming. Or is it? Are droughts a godsend to controlling <span style=\"font-family: \'Helvetica Neue Light\', HelveticaNeue-Light, helvetica, arial, sans-serif;\">ocean levels which are adversely increasing from melting glaciers? I doubt it...</span><div><div><br></div><div>I believe in God, to fix our planet. But somehow, The Lord is making us figure it out on our own. Or does he want us to worship him more? No, only a despot would ask of such a thing. I believe The Lord is omnipotent and omnibenevolent. Is he truly both? Or is he merely experimenting this planet like he\'s been for the past 65,000,000 years? There are limited resources, like water, oil and coal which there could be no more of by 2080. If that were to happen, this planet will die along with them, like Venus, the volcanic armpit of our Solar System, or Mars, the rusty wasteland of a planet.</div></div><div><br></div><div>If I were God, I would have the power to make things better than let things get worse. Or can that be making things worse than things getting worse altogether?!</div>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:64:\"http://miletich2.blogspot.com/2014/08/stupid-climate-change.html\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:6:\"author\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:26:\"noreply@blogger.com (Zack)\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:1:{s:7:\"updated\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"2014-08-03T22:01:29.158-07:00\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0\";a:1:{s:5:\"total\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:19;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:70:\"tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-3424051896540341526.post-3091863920631975731\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Fri, 01 Aug 2014 04:12:00 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:16:\"Metroid Wii-boot\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1201:\"Metroid is Nintendo\'s sci-fi franchise in its arsenal of gaming legends. In 1986 or 87, we witnessed the birth of Samus Aran, a bounty hunter raised on Zebes, who becomes the galaxy\'s greatest warrior who takes on space pirate and a swarm of life-sucking parasites called Metroids.<div><br></div><div>But since Nintendo is struggling to get back on top, I figured Metroid could use a reboot. By a reboot, I mean seeing Metroid as a first-person horror shooter with the same sci-fi elements as well as those from the legendary Metroid Prime trilogy. I would see Metroids as scary and hungry enemies of Samus Aran that threaten the galaxy. I would also like it mature-rated, but not to the extent of the Dead Space series. Additionally, I\'d prefer if the main antagonist of the reboot were a corrupt CO instead of a fire breathing dragon called Ridley or a Godzilla-esque beast with spikes on its belly and three eyes!</div><div><br></div><div>It seems like Nintendo is squandering their canonical resources in the Metroid franchise. That\'s how the idea came in my head. Star Fox could use a reboot, too. Won\'t be the first time, but there\'s a Wii U game of Star Fox. Hope it\'s worth to check out.</div>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:59:\"http://miletich2.blogspot.com/2014/07/metroid-wii-boot.html\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:6:\"author\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:26:\"noreply@blogger.com (Zack)\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:1:{s:7:\"updated\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"2014-07-31T21:12:55.561-07:00\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0\";a:1:{s:5:\"total\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:20;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:70:\"tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-3424051896540341526.post-5876754168598968971\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Tue, 29 Jul 2014 22:27:00 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:21:\"Any other Miletiches?\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:697:\"I\'m talking about people whose last name is Miletich, besides my cousins, uncle, sisters, kid brother and parents. As I\'m sure some of you know. It\'s pronounced <b><i>mill-uh-titch</i></b>. I know there\'s a Pat Miletich, a martial artist who was recently inducted in the UFC hall of fame. If I were to get married, I would be able to start my own family and keep the \"Miletich\" population intact. But since I\'m autistic, I can\'t be bothered to take the risk of giving up my favorite gaming hobbies.<div><br></div><div>Miletich... One of the most uncommon last names all around the globe. Much less, America. All I would want to remain are at least a few families whose last name is Miletich.</div>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:63:\"http://miletich2.blogspot.com/2014/07/any-other-miletiches.html\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:6:\"author\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:26:\"noreply@blogger.com (Zack)\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:1:{s:7:\"updated\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"2014-07-29T15:36:22.322-07:00\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0\";a:1:{s:5:\"total\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:21;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:70:\"tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-3424051896540341526.post-8378420400424685296\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Fri, 25 Jul 2014 05:24:00 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:23:\"I wish I was omniscient\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1890:\"Even more so than wishing I was omnipotent. To be omniscient means you\'re all-knowing. Can\'t say that\'s possible because as long as you live, you\'re bound to learn and then you die without the chance of being omniscient. Speaking of which, here\'s what I\'m talking about.<div><br></div><div>When you\'re omniscient, you can foresee the very future countless years ahead of time. You can also see how a government body is performing at ruling a country. And you can even find the ultimate solution to global warming/climate change. But I wouldn\'t be omniscient to read the minds of others, reveal anyone\'s intentions or to be omnifortunate. All-lucky, that is!</div><div><br></div><div>The internet....</div><div><br></div><div>Is not absolutely omniscient. In fact, some articles I see on the news are either a fog of lies or a fog of irrationality in the case of politics. There are fogs of irrationality in other topics, too.</div><div><br></div><div>Some conservatives say liberalism is a disorder and I am disgusted that many Americans support this blasted theory! I don\'t care if it makes you less defensive of your own decisions, whether they\'re selfish or selfless. I am just plain offended by those who say it. If I were omniscient, I would find the answer to this dilemma. Then I could prove to the world that liberalism never was, nor should it be called, a disorder! There needs to be reform in some areas! There needs to be equality to help all Americans thrive in the harshest conditions!</div><div><br></div><div>If you\'re still reading, I\'m sure you know conservatism isn\'t a mental disorder, either. But it can cause worry of potentially \"destructive\" changes that will occur in time. But don\'t let that dissuade you from being a conservative or a Republican. Liberalism can be dangerous, too, though. When it comes to financial data, medical records or private affairs.</div>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:66:\"http://miletich2.blogspot.com/2014/07/i-wish-i-was-omniscient.html\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:6:\"author\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:26:\"noreply@blogger.com (Zack)\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:1:{s:7:\"updated\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"2014-07-24T22:24:22.532-07:00\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0\";a:1:{s:5:\"total\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:22;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:70:\"tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-3424051896540341526.post-1714439061878774562\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Thu, 10 Jul 2014 22:30:00 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"California...\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1087:\"Not the state I assumed all my life it was. In Christmas, there is snowfall, but not here. We all live in a Mediterranean climate, where it <i style=\"font-weight: bold;\">rains in winter. </i>But what\'s worse than rain... Is none! AKA, a drought.<div><br></div><div>Mother Nature can be so despicable sometimes, even when fixing something, but at the same time ruining something else. I had a funny feeling solar panels were linked to this dry hell we are in now. But as I thought, they\'re a godsend, good for fighting power outages.</div><div><br></div><div>Our California may be turning into a desert. It\'s an unwelcome change. We need rain! Here is what\'s causing us to get ridiculously less rain.&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.weatherwest.com/archives/tag/ridiculously-resilient-ridge\" style=\"font-family: \'Helvetica Neue Light\', HelveticaNeue-Light, helvetica, arial, sans-serif;\">http://www.weatherwest.com/archives/tag/ridiculously-resilient-ridge</a></div><div><br></div><div>Mother Nature, if you don\'t obliterate this ridiculously resilient ridge, we won\'t worship you anymore!</div>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:53:\"http://miletich2.blogspot.com/2014/07/california.html\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:6:\"author\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:26:\"noreply@blogger.com (Zack)\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:1:{s:7:\"updated\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"2014-07-10T15:30:46.693-07:00\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0\";a:1:{s:5:\"total\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:23;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:70:\"tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-3424051896540341526.post-3494187352376401253\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Wed, 02 Jul 2014 18:37:00 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"Celebrity marriages\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:889:\"They tend to be rather dicey, because you have commitments as an actor, musician and everything else you\'re famous for. When celebrity couples divorce, it\'s like a stab in the back. It makes me a bit sad, although they\'re fairly common nowadays. But this one came as a sudden shocker to me. Jewel, a country singer and her hubby, Ty, have officially announced their divorce. I once thought all divorces ended in partners having contempt and hatred for ech other. But that\'s only after one partner feels animosity towards the other for infidelity, spousal abuse or other crimes. But now I see divorce as a reset switch, to undo any destructive changes that\'s happened in their lives.<div><br></div><div>Usually, I thought partners who love each other stay together until the very end. But some split couples could choose to remain friends. Hopefully Ty and Jewel will still hold that.</div>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:62:\"http://miletich2.blogspot.com/2014/07/celebrity-marriages.html\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:6:\"author\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:26:\"noreply@blogger.com (Zack)\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:1:{s:7:\"updated\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"2014-07-02T11:37:33.915-07:00\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0\";a:1:{s:5:\"total\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:24;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:69:\"tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-3424051896540341526.post-301550235528065958\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Sat, 14 Jun 2014 21:43:00 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:11:\"Love my job\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:2666:\"It can be tedious as watching the grass grow millimeter by millimeter. But damn it! It\'s my means of making money, making friends and also serving customers to the limit. It\'s an experience I shan\'t forget because as long as I\'ve been living at home without school or work, especially in the hot summertime, life was just empty. I work at a thrift store in Lafayette, CA. I have a beautiful job coach, a fairly stern manager, a flexible transit system and a few companions who run the register. This is my idea of living the American dream!<div><br></div><div>Now, the concept itself doesn\'t have to be, nor can it be, all opulent or free of difficulty. Otherwise, you\'re in a world of emptiness. I&nbsp;<span style=\"font-family: \'Helvetica Neue Light\', HelveticaNeue-Light, helvetica, arial, sans-serif;\">have goals such as renting my own apartment. But it can\'t be rushed since the housing department is corrupt around here.</span></div><div><span style=\"font-family: \'Helvetica Neue Light\', HelveticaNeue-Light, helvetica, arial, sans-serif;\"><br></span></div><div><span style=\"font-family: \'Helvetica Neue Light\', HelveticaNeue-Light, helvetica, arial, sans-serif;\">There are others who feel they no longer embrace the American dream because they relentlessly blame President Obama and his healthcare law, Obamacare. While I see Obama as a godsend who helps the poor and those hurt by climate change, others feel harm during his presidency. Fortunately for the Obama administration, my job isn\'t in jeopardy as some in Texas, North Carolina and in other non-democratic states are.</span></div><div><span style=\"font-family: \'Helvetica Neue Light\', HelveticaNeue-Light, helvetica, arial, sans-serif;\"><br></span></div><div><font face=\"Helvetica Neue Light, HelveticaNeue-Light, helvetica, arial, sans-serif\">I still loathe George W. Bush, but a lot of people are starting to like him now because he\'s either out of office or Obama is doing more harm to this country than the former was! So much harm several Americans are now crying for the president\'s impeachment. Midterm elections are coming this November and I\'m not gonna lie to you my friends. I don\'t care if the republicans or democrats win the midterm elections. If there is any political party who I feel should rule America more than elephants or donkeys, it\'s either a libertarian or independent party. I wish for a government with narrower tax brackets, proper immigration control and a revised second amendment that grants citizens access to control if, and only if, they\'ve been constantly victimized by potential terrorists, radical gangs or absolute left-wing or absolute right-wing.</font></div>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:54:\"http://miletich2.blogspot.com/2014/06/love-my-job.html\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:6:\"author\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:26:\"noreply@blogger.com (Zack)\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:1:{s:7:\"updated\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"2014-06-16T14:27:32.661-07:00\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0\";a:1:{s:5:\"total\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}}}s:39:\"http://a9.com/-/spec/opensearchrss/1.0/\";a:3:{s:12:\"totalResults\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:3:\"368\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:10:\"startIndex\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:12:\"itemsPerPage\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:2:\"25\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}}}}}}}}s:4:\"type\";i:128;s:7:\"headers\";a:13:{s:16:\"content-encoding\";s:4:\"gzip\";s:4:\"etag\";s:40:\"W/\"e00bb9dd-804d-4101-b0e1-663f203aad3b\"\";s:4:\"date\";s:29:\"Thu, 21 Apr 2016 13:39:33 GMT\";s:12:\"content-type\";s:34:\"application/rss+xml; charset=UTF-8\";s:6:\"server\";s:15:\"blogger-renderd\";s:13:\"cache-control\";s:52:\"public, must-revalidate, proxy-revalidate, max-age=1\";s:4:\"vary\";s:15:\"Accept-Encoding\";s:7:\"expires\";s:29:\"Thu, 21 Apr 2016 13:39:34 GMT\";s:22:\"x-content-type-options\";s:7:\"nosniff\";s:16:\"x-xss-protection\";s:13:\"1; mode=block\";s:13